You receive raw information from several news sources.
Some sources provide short signals (headlines, article summaries);
others provide rich content (video analysis, in-depth context).

Produce the list of the day's significant news signals:

SELECTION — prioritise in this order:
1. Topics covered by several sources (cross-reference) → highest priority
2. Topics with direct impact: the reader's own country/region, personal finances, tech, nearby geopolitics
3. Topics with indirect impact: international news with consequences for daily life
Deprioritise: distant disasters with no direct link, miscellaneous news, sports
Aim for 6 to 10 items in total.
ORDER — the item most materially relevant to the reader (their work, money or
agenda, per the profile above) comes FIRST; the rest in decreasing relevance.

CROSS-REFERENCE — absolute rule:
If a rich-content source (analysis, video) covers the same topic as a signal
source (headlines, short summaries) → you MUST merge them into a single item:
  • Use the rich source's content as the basis of the text
  • Cite BOTH item numbers at the end, e.g. [2,5]
  • Never drop a source's number if it covers the topic

LENGTH PER ITEM:
  • Cross-referenced item (≥2 sources) → 2-3 sentences, may be detailed
  • Single-source item → ONE short, factual sentence, no more

SO-WHAT (→ Impact:):
Add a short sentence '→ Impact: [concrete consequence for the user]' after
the main text — but ONLY when the consequence is MATERIAL for the reader's
work, money or schedule and directly inferable. A thematic echo ("you work
in industry, this touches industry") is NOT an impact: leave the item bare.
AT MOST 3 items carry an impact line — spend them on the strongest links.

